  "prompt": "How do insurance deductibles work?",
  "response": "An insurance deductible is the amount you pay out of pocket for covered expenses before your insurance coverage kicks in. Here's how it typically works:\n\n1. Fixed amount\n- Deductibles are a set dollar amount (e.g., $500, $1,000, $2,500)\n- You pay this amount first when filing a claim\n\n2. Per-incident or annual\n- Some deductibles apply to each incident\n- Others are annual, meaning you pay the deductible once per year\n\n3. Impact on premiums\n- Higher deductibles usually mean lower monthly insurance premiums\n- Lower deductibles mean higher monthly premiums\n\n4. Example\n- If you have a $1,000 deductible and $5,000 in medical expenses\n- You pay the first $1,000\n- Insurance covers the remaining $4,000\n\n5. Varies by insurance type\n- Health, auto, and homeowners insurance all use deductibles differently\n- Some have percentage-based deductibles instead of fixed amounts\n\n6. Considerations\n- Choose a deductible you can afford to pay\n- Balance between monthly premium and out-of-pocket costs\n\nThe specific details can vary depending on your insurance type and provider.",
